  "prompt": "Do candles spoil?",
  "response": "Candles don't spoil in the way that food does, but they can degrade over time depending on their composition and how they're stored. Here are a few factors to consider:\n\n1. **Wax Type**: Different types of wax (paraffin, soy, beeswax, etc.) have varying lifespans. For instance, soy candles generally have a shorter shelf life than beeswax candles due to the natural properties of the wax.\n\n2. **Fragrance and Additives**: The essential oils or synthetic fragrances added to candles can lose their scent potency over time. Additionally, additives used in the wax can affect the candle's performance and appearance.\n\n3. **Storage Conditions**: Exposure to heat, light, and moisture can negatively impact candles. Storing them in a cool, dry place, away from direct sunlight, can help maintain their quality.\n\n4. **Wick Quality**: The wick's materials can degrade, affecting the candle's ability to burn properly.\n\nWhile candles can last a long time (several years) if stored correctly, it's always a good idea to check for any signs of deterioration, such as unusual smells, discoloration, or changes in texture before use.",
